body:
The sooner we get clear on what we want to support the better.

It would also be good to clarify whether we want tiers of support in order to provide the best experience in each product or shoot for a lowest common denominator that works equally well in all but sub-optimally in some.

cc @devoncarew

comment_data.body:
Excellent question! We should discuss, but my initial take on it would be:
- IntelliJ Community Edition (it's free to end users)
- IntelliJ Ultimate (a superset of CE)
- Android Studio (to appeal to existing Android developers)

And opportunistically AppCode, to round out an iOS story.

Fully agree we need to support CE and Ultimate. 

I'd like to understand the likely workflows in Android Studio better. Is the idea just that they already have it installed, so it would be one step less to experiment with a first Flutter app?

> @pq do you have a concrete example of what kind of issue we might get?

This is something we should carve out some time to explore.

The main things I'm aware of are largely UI and flow-centered.  In particular, project creation and management is different in IDEs that support multiple modules per project (IDEA) versus only one (the "smaller" IDE offerings (such as I presume CE).

> I'd like to understand the likely workflows in Android Studio better. 

Me too! :)  Sounds like an AI... üëç
Let's assume IntelliJ CE and ultimate for now, and open specific issues for additional platforms (Android Studio, AppCode) to track the work for those products, when we do want to support them.

title: Identify what IntelliJ products we want to support (and how).
